<h3>Defining Entrepreneurship</h3>
<p>Entrepreneurship is the process of identifying a problem, creating a solution, building an organisation around it, and taking the risk of bringing that solution to market. An entrepreneur is someone who creates value where none existed before.</p>
<p>It is not just about starting a business. It is about seeing the world differently — spotting opportunities where others see obstacles, and having the discipline and courage to act on them.</p>
<h3>Types of Entrepreneurs</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Small Business Entrepreneur</strong> — Runs a local business: tailors, restaurants, mechanics, market traders. The backbone of African economies.</li>
<li><strong>Scalable Startup Entrepreneur</strong> — Builds a business designed to grow rapidly and serve millions. Flutterwave, Paystack, and Jumia started here.</li>
<li><strong>Social Entrepreneur</strong> — Solves social or environmental problems through business models. M-PESA transformed financial inclusion across Africa.</li>
<li><strong>Corporate Entrepreneur (Intrapreneur)</strong> — Innovates within an existing company, creating new products or divisions.</li>
<li><strong>Lifestyle Entrepreneur</strong> — Builds a business around their preferred lifestyle, prioritising freedom over rapid growth.</li>
<li><strong>Serial Entrepreneur</strong> — Starts multiple businesses, often exits one and starts another. Elon Musk, Tony Elumelu.</li>
</ul>
<h3>The Mindset Shift</h3>
<p>Most people are trained to be employees — to follow instructions, complete tasks, and receive a salary. Entrepreneurs must unlearn this. The entrepreneurial mindset requires:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Ownership thinking</strong> — You are responsible for outcomes, not just activities</li>
<li><strong>Comfort with uncertainty</strong> — No guaranteed salary, no clear roadmap</li>
<li><strong>Problem obsession</strong> — Falling in love with the problem, not your solution</li>
<li><strong>Resilience</strong> — Treating failure as data, not defeat</li>
<li><strong>Long-term orientation</strong> — Planting trees whose shade you may never sit under</li>
</ul>
<h3>Why Africa Needs More Entrepreneurs</h3>
<p>Africa has over 1.4 billion people, a median age of 19, and growing smartphone penetration. The continent has problems that need solving — in healthcare, education, agriculture, energy, logistics, and finance. Every problem is a business opportunity. The next Flutterwave, Andela, or Twiga Foods starts with someone deciding to be an entrepreneur today.</p>
<div class="africa-box"><span class="africa-title">&#127757; African Context</span>
Nigeria alone has over 37 million SMEs accounting for 48% of national GDP. Ghana, Kenya, and South Africa are growing startup ecosystems with increasing access to funding. African entrepreneurs who understand their local markets have an advantage that no foreign company can easily replicate.
</div>
