<h3>Problem vs Opportunity</h3>
<p>Not every problem is a business opportunity. An opportunity exists when there is a problem that is <strong>painful enough</strong> for people to pay to have it solved, and when you have a <strong>realistic way to solve it</strong> that others do not yet offer — or offer poorly.</p>
<p>The three conditions for a real opportunity:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>The pain is real</strong> — People are actively suffering or frustrated</li>
<li><strong>The market is large enough</strong> — Enough people have this problem to build a sustainable business</li>
<li><strong>You can solve it better</strong> — You have an insight, approach, or resource advantage</li>
</ol>
<h3>Where to Find Opportunities</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Your own frustrations</strong> — What problems do you encounter daily that have no good solution?</li>
<li><strong>Underserved communities</strong> — Who is being ignored by existing businesses? Rural areas, informal workers, women entrepreneurs, youth</li>
<li><strong>Technology shifts</strong> — What does a new technology (mobile internet, AI, cheap sensors) now make possible?</li>
<li><strong>Regulatory changes</strong> — New laws create new markets. CBN's open banking policy created fintech opportunities.</li>
<li><strong>Imported ideas</strong> — What works in another market that has not yet arrived in yours?</li>
<li><strong>Broken systems</strong> — Healthcare, education, logistics, power — which systems are failing people?</li>
</ul>
<h3>Jobs-to-be-Done Theory</h3>
<p>Developed by Clayton Christensen at Harvard, this framework says: <em>customers do not buy products — they hire them to do a job.</em> When you understand the job the customer is trying to get done, you can design far better solutions.</p>
<p>Example: People do not want a drill. They want a hole in the wall. They actually want to hang a picture. What they really want is a beautiful home. Understanding each level reveals different opportunities.</p>
<h3>Opportunity Validation Questions</h3>
<ul>
<li>Who exactly has this problem? Can I name 10 specific people?</li>
<li>How do they currently solve it? Why is that solution inadequate?</li>
<li>How much does this problem cost them — in money, time, or frustration?</li>
<li>Would they pay for a better solution? How much?</li>
<li>Is the problem growing, stable, or shrinking?</li>
</ul>
