<h3>Why Customer Discovery?</h3>
<p>The number one reason startups fail is that they build something nobody wants. Customer discovery is the systematic process of testing your assumptions about who your customer is and what they truly need — <em>before</em> you spend significant time or money building a product.</p>
<p>Steve Blank, the father of the Lean Startup methodology, said: <strong>"Get out of the building."</strong> Your assumptions are not facts until real customers confirm them.</p>
<h3>The Mom Test</h3>
<p>The Mom Test (Rob Fitzpatrick) is a framework for asking questions your mom cannot lie to you about. Even your mom will lie to make you feel good about your idea. The solution is to stop asking about your idea and start asking about their life.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bad question</strong>: "Do you think this app is a good idea?" — People will say yes to be polite</li>
<li><strong>Good question</strong>: "Tell me about the last time you tried to solve this problem. What did you do?"</li>
<li><strong>Bad question</strong>: "Would you pay for something like this?"</li>
<li><strong>Good question</strong>: "How much does this problem currently cost you? Have you paid for solutions before?"</li>
</ul>
<h3>How to Conduct a Customer Interview</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Set context</strong> — Thank them, explain you are doing research (not selling)</li>
<li><strong>Ask about the past</strong> — Past behaviour is the best predictor of future behaviour</li>
<li><strong>Dig for specifics</strong> — "Tell me more about that" / "What happened next?"</li>
<li><strong>Listen more than you talk</strong> — Aim for 80% them, 20% you</li>
<li><strong>Never pitch</strong> — The moment you pitch, they stop giving honest feedback</li>
<li><strong>Take notes</strong> — Write down their exact words, not your interpretation</li>
</ol>
<h3>What to Look For</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Emotional language</strong> — "It drives me crazy", "I hate how...", "I wish there was..." These signal real pain</li>
<li><strong>Workarounds</strong> — When people have built their own clunky solution, that is proof the problem is real</li>
<li><strong>Money already spent</strong> — If they are already paying for an imperfect solution, they will pay for a better one</li>
<li><strong>Frequency</strong> — How often does this problem occur? Daily problems are better than annual ones</li>
</ul>
<h3>How Many Interviews?</h3>
<p>Start with 10–20 interviews from your target customer group. By interview 10, you will start hearing the same patterns. This is called <strong>saturation</strong> — the point where additional interviews stop revealing new insights.</p>
