<h3>The Validation Imperative</h3>
<p>An idea is worth nothing until it is validated. Validation means finding evidence from real people that your solution addresses a real problem and that people will pay for it — <strong>before</strong> you spend significant time or money building.</p>
<h3>Types of Validation — Cheapest to Most Expensive</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Conversation validation</strong> — Customer interviews. Lowest cost, least binding evidence.</li>
<li><strong>Smoke tests</strong> — Create a landing page describing your product and measure sign-up rates before the product exists.</li>
<li><strong>Pre-selling</strong> — Sell the product before it is built. If people pay, demand is validated.</li>
<li><strong>Concierge MVP</strong> — Deliver the service manually before automating. Prove people want it, then build the tech.</li>
<li><strong>Pilot programs</strong> — Serve a small number of real customers in a controlled test.</li>
</ol>
<h3>The Smoke Test</h3>
<p>Build a simple webpage describing your product, benefits, and price. Add a Get Early Access button. Drive 100–500 people to the page. Measure click-through rate, email sign-ups, and pre-orders. A 10%+ email conversion suggests genuine interest. Pre-orders are the gold standard.</p>
<h3>The Concierge MVP</h3>
<p>Food Rocket delivered groceries by having people WhatsApp orders to a person who physically went to the market. No app, no warehouse system — just a human proving the concept. Once demand was confirmed, they built the technology. This approach works for delivery, marketplace, SaaS, consulting, education, and many more categories.</p>
<h3>Pre-Selling</h3>
<p>Tell potential customers your product is in development and offer them a discounted early price. This validates demand AND gives you working capital. Kickstarter built an entire platform on this concept.</p>
<h3>What Counts as Validation?</h3>
<ul>
<li>&#10003; People pre-pay or commit money</li>
<li>&#10003; Signed letters of intent from business customers</li>
<li>&#10003; High opt-in rate on a smoke test (10%+)</li>
<li>&#10003; Customers using your concierge MVP repeatedly</li>
<li>&#10007; Friends and family saying great idea</li>
<li>&#10007; Online surveys with hypothetical answers</li>
</ul>
