    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-7">
<h3>What is a Value Proposition?</h3>
<p>Your value proposition is a clear statement that explains how your product solves your customer's problem, what benefits it delivers, and why they should choose you over alternatives. It is the most important piece of copy in your entire business.</p>
<h3>The Value Proposition Formula</h3>
<p>A strong value proposition answers:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Relevance</strong> — How does your product solve the customer's problem?</li>
<li><strong>Quantified value</strong> — What specific benefit does it deliver? Save time, reduce cost, increase revenue.</li>
<li><strong>Differentiation</strong> — Why choose you over alternatives?</li>
</ol>
<h3>The Value Proposition Canvas</h3>
<p><strong>Customer Profile:</strong> Customer Jobs (what they are trying to do), Pains (frustrations), Gains (what they hope for).<br>
<strong>Value Map:</strong> Products and Services, Pain Relievers (how you reduce pain), Gain Creators (how you create gains).<br>
Product-market fit happens when your pain relievers and gain creators perfectly match customer pains and gains.</p>
<h3>Strong vs Weak Value Propositions</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Weak:</strong> "We provide excellent quality services at affordable prices." — Generic, says nothing specific.</li>
<li><strong>Strong:</strong> "We help small business owners in Lagos collect payments from anywhere in Nigeria in under 60 seconds, with zero monthly fees." — Specific customer, specific benefit, specific differentiator.</li>
</ul>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Value proposition</strong> — Clear statement of how you solve a problem better than alternatives<br>
<strong>Differentiation</strong> — What makes your solution different and better<br>
<strong>Product-market fit</strong> — When your value map perfectly addresses the customer profile<br>
<strong>Customer pains</strong> — Frustrations, risks and obstacles customers experience
