    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(8)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-8">08</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Market Research and Sizing</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">TAM SAM SOM, primary vs secondary research, competition analysis</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-8"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-8">&#8964;</div></div>
    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-8">
<h3>TAM, SAM, SOM — Sizing Your Market</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>TAM (Total Addressable Market)</strong> — The total global revenue opportunity if you captured 100% of the market.</li>
<li><strong>SAM (Serviceable Addressable Market)</strong> — The portion of TAM you can realistically serve with your current model and geography.</li>
<li><strong>SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market)</strong> — The portion of SAM you can realistically capture in the next 1-3 years.</li>
</ul>
<p>Investors want a TAM of at least $1 billion (large enough prize), a credible SAM, and a realistic SOM with a clear path to capture it.</p>
<h3>Primary vs Secondary Research</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Primary research</strong> — You collect original data: interviews, surveys, observations, experiments. Most valuable but takes time.</li>
<li><strong>Secondary research</strong> — You use existing data: industry reports, government statistics, competitor analysis. Faster but less specific.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Competitor Analysis</h3>
<p>For each key competitor document: What they offer, pricing, target customer, strengths, weaknesses, market share, and recent moves. Then identify your gap — what they are not doing that customers need.</p>
