    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(10)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-10">10</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Finance for Founders</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">P&L, cash flow, burn rate, runway, unit economics, CAC, LTV</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-10"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-10">&#8964;</div></div>
    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-10">
<h3>Why Founders Must Understand Finance</h3>
<p>You do not need to be an accountant. But you must understand concepts that determine whether your business survives. Founders who ignore their numbers make decisions that slowly kill their company without realising it.</p>
<h3>The Three Core Financial Statements</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Profit and Loss (P&amp;L)</strong> — Revenue, costs, and profit or loss over a period. Revenue minus COGS = Gross Profit. Gross Profit minus OpEx = Net Profit.</li>
<li><strong>Balance Sheet</strong> — What you own (assets), what you owe (liabilities), and what is left (equity) at a specific moment.</li>
<li><strong>Cash Flow Statement</strong> — Actual cash moving in and out. Profitable companies can go bankrupt from poor cash flow.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Key Early-Stage Metrics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Burn rate</strong> — How much cash you spend per month.</li>
<li><strong>Runway</strong> — Cash ÷ Monthly Burn = months you can survive.</li>
<li><strong>Gross margin</strong> — (Revenue - COGS) ÷ Revenue. Sell for 500, costs 200: (500-200)/500 = 60% margin.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Unit Economics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>CAC (Customer Acquisition Cost)</strong> — Total marketing spend ÷ customers acquired.</li>
<li><strong>LTV (Lifetime Value)</strong> — Total revenue from one customer over their entire relationship.</li>
<li><strong>LTV:CAC ratio</strong> — Should be at least 3:1. If LTV is ₦30k and CAC is ₦10k, ratio = 3:1. Healthy business.</li>
</ul>
