    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(12)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-12">12</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Funding Your Startup</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Bootstrapping, angels, VCs, grants, debt, crowdfunding stages</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-12"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-12">&#8964;</div></div>
    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-12">
<h3>The Funding Landscape</h3>
<p>There is no single right way to fund a startup. The best source depends on your stage, industry, growth rate, and how much control you want. Most startups use a combination of sources over time.</p>
<h3>Types of Funding</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Bootstrapping</strong> — Self-funding. Keep 100% equity and control. Best when you can generate revenue quickly.</li>
<li><strong>Friends and Family</strong> — First external capital. Informal but must be documented to prevent relationship damage.</li>
<li><strong>Grants</strong> — Non-repayable funding. Tony Elumelu Foundation ($5,000), YouWiN, CBN MSME funds, Google for Startups. Competitive but free money.</li>
<li><strong>Angel Investors</strong> — High net-worth individuals who invest personal funds for equity. Typically $10k–$250k.</li>
<li><strong>Venture Capital</strong> — Professional firms investing in high-growth startups for equity. Rounds: Pre-seed, Seed, Series A, B, C+.</li>
<li><strong>Debt / Bank Loans</strong> — Borrow and repay with interest. No equity lost but requires collateral and consistent cash flow.</li>
<li><strong>Crowdfunding</strong> — Small amounts from many people. Reward-based (Kickstarter) or equity-based (Republic, StartEngine).</li>
<li><strong>Revenue-based financing</strong> — Capital in exchange for percentage of future revenues until a multiple is repaid.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Funding Stages</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pre-seed</strong> — Idea/concept stage. Founder savings, FFF, grants. Up to $500k.</li>
<li><strong>Seed</strong> — MVP built, early customers. Angels, seed VCs. $500k–$3M.</li>
<li><strong>Series A</strong> — Proven PMF, scaling. VC firms. $3M–$15M.</li>
<li><strong>Series B+</strong> — Rapid scaling. Large VCs and growth equity. $15M+.</li>
</ul>
<div class="africa-box"><span class="africa-title">&#127757; African Funding Sources</span>
Tony Elumelu Foundation, Ventures Platform, Techstars Africa, Y Combinator (accepts African startups), Google for Startups Africa, VC4A, Founders Factory Africa, CBN MSME fund, and state government entrepreneurship programmes.
</div>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Equity</strong> — Ownership share given in exchange for investment<br>
<strong>Angel investor</strong> — Individual investing personal funds in early startups<br>
<strong>VC</strong> — Venture Capital: professional firm funding high-growth startups<br>
<strong>Dilution</strong> — Reduction in existing ownership percentage when new shares are issued
