    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(15)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-15">15</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Pricing Strategy</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Cost-plus, value-based, penetration, anchoring, tiered pricing</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-15"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-15">&#8964;</div></div>
    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-15">
<h3>Why Pricing is Strategic</h3>
<p>Pricing is one of the highest leverage decisions you make. It directly affects revenue, profitability, the type of customers you attract, and how your brand is perceived. Most early-stage founders underprice — out of fear or modesty — and this is a strategic mistake.</p>
<h3>Core Pricing Strategies</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cost-plus pricing</strong> — Calculate your costs, add a margin. Simple but ignores value. Example: costs ₦500, sell for ₦750 (50% margin).</li>
<li><strong>Value-based pricing</strong> — Price based on the value the customer receives, not your costs. If your software saves a business ₦500k/month, charging ₦50k/month is still cheap to them.</li>
<li><strong>Competitive pricing</strong> — Price relative to competitors. Can work but invites a price war.</li>
<li><strong>Penetration pricing</strong> — Enter at very low price to gain market share, then raise prices. Risky: customers resist price increases.</li>
<li><strong>Skimming</strong> — Start high for early adopters who value novelty, lower price over time as market matures.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Pricing Psychology Tactics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Anchoring</strong> — Show a higher price first. ₦25,000 looks cheap next to ₦75,000.</li>
<li><strong>Charm pricing</strong> — ₦4,999 feels cheaper than ₦5,000.</li>
<li><strong>Tiered pricing</strong> — Basic, Standard, Premium. The middle tier usually sells most. Used by Zoom, Dropbox, Notion.</li>
<li><strong>Decoy pricing</strong> — Add a third option that makes your preferred option look like better value.</li>
</ul>
<h3>The Danger of Underpricing</h3>
<ul>
<li>Signals low quality to customers</li>
<li>Attracts price-sensitive customers who are hardest to retain</li>
<li>Makes it difficult to raise prices later without backlash</li>
<li>Kills your margins and makes you unprofitable</li>
</ul>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Price elasticity</strong> — How sensitive demand is to price changes<br>
<strong>Value-based pricing</strong> — Pricing based on customer value received, not your costs<br>
<strong>Price anchoring</strong> — Using a high reference price to make actual price seem reasonable<br>
<strong>CAC payback period</strong> — Months until revenue from a customer covers their acquisition cost
