    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(18)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-18">18</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Product Development and MVP</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">MVP types, agile, sprints, Build-Measure-Learn, product-market fit</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-18"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-18">&#8964;</div></div>
    <div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-18">
<h3>The MVP Concept</h3>
<p>A Minimum Viable Product is the version of your product with just enough features to satisfy early adopters and collect validated feedback for future development. The goal is not to build the best product — it is to learn the most, fastest, with minimum waste.</p>
<p>Famous MVPs: Dropbox launched with just a demo video (no product). Airbnb's founders rented out air mattresses in their own apartment. Zappos bought shoes from a store and manually fulfilled orders before building a warehouse system.</p>
<h3>Types of MVPs</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Landing page MVP</strong> — Describe the product, collect emails or pre-orders. Zero development.</li>
<li><strong>Concierge MVP</strong> — Deliver the service manually before automating.</li>
<li><strong>Wizard of Oz MVP</strong> — Looks automated to users but is actually powered by humans behind the scenes.</li>
<li><strong>Single feature MVP</strong> — Build only the one core feature that solves the main problem.</li>
<li><strong>Prototype MVP</strong> — A clickable mockup for user testing without back-end development.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Agile Development</h3>
<p>Build in short cycles (sprints of 1-2 weeks). Each sprint delivers working features. Get feedback. Improve. Repeat. This beats the old waterfall method of building for 12 months and launching a product nobody wants.</p>
<h3>Product-Market Fit</h3>
<p>Sean Ellis's test: Ask your users "How would you feel if you could no longer use this product?" If 40%+ say "Very disappointed" — you have product-market fit. Below 40%, keep iterating.</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>MVP</strong> — Minimum Viable Product: simplest version to test core assumptions<br>
<strong>Agile</strong> — Iterative development methodology with short cycles and continuous feedback<br>
<strong>Sprint</strong> — Short time-boxed development cycle (1-2 weeks)<br>
<strong>Technical debt</strong> — Code shortcuts that save time now but cause problems later<br>
<strong>PMF</strong> — Product-Market Fit: when your market loves your product
