  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-23" data-lesson="23"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(23)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-23">23</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Leadership and Team Management</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Leadership styles, psychological safety, SBI feedback, EQ, culture</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-23"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-23">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-23"><h3>The Founder Leadership Journey</h3>
<p>Early stage: founders do everything. By 20+ people, your primary job is enabling others to do great work. This transition — from doer to enabler — is one of the hardest shifts founders face.</p>
<h3>What Great Leaders Do</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Set clear vision</strong> — Every person knows where the company is going and why</li>
<li><strong>Build psychological safety</strong> — Team members speak up honestly without fear of punishment</li>
<li><strong>Give and receive feedback</strong> — Regular honest feedback is how teams improve</li>
<li><strong>Develop people</strong> — The best leaders make their people better every week</li>
<li><strong>Decide with incomplete data</strong> — Make the best call available, communicate clearly, course-correct fast</li>
</ul>
<h3>The SBI Feedback Framework</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Situation</strong> — "In yesterday's client meeting..."</li>
<li><strong>Behaviour</strong> — "...you interrupted the client three times..."</li>
<li><strong>Impact</strong> — "...which made them uncomfortable and may affect the deal."</li>
</ul>
<h3>Google Project Aristotle</h3>
<p>Google's 5-year study on team performance found that <strong>psychological safety</strong> — not individual talent, seniority, or IQ — was the single most important factor in team effectiveness. Teams that feel safe generate more ideas, surface problems early, and take creative risks needed for innovation.</p>
<h3>Emotional Intelligence (EQ)</h3>
<p>EQ in leadership means: self-awareness (know your triggers), self-regulation (manage your reactions), empathy (understand others' perspectives), social skills (build relationships), and motivation (internal drive beyond money).</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Psychological safety</strong> — Ability to speak up without fear of punishment<br>
<strong>SBI feedback</strong> — Situation, Behaviour, Impact: structured feedback model<br>
<strong>Servant leadership</strong> — Leader prioritises team needs and growth<br>
<strong>EQ</strong> — Emotional Intelligence: recognise, understand, manage emotions
