  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-24" data-lesson="24"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(24)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-24">24</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Entrepreneurship in Africa</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">African context, leapfrogging, informal economy, AfCFTA, ecosystem</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-24"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-24">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-24"><h3>Africa — The World's Greatest Opportunity</h3>
<p>Africa has 1.4 billion people, a median age of 19 years, the world's fastest-growing middle class, and the greatest concentration of unsolved human problems in healthcare, education, energy, agriculture, and finance. Every major problem is a major business opportunity waiting for an African founder to solve it.</p>
<h3>What Makes Africa Unique</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Leapfrogging</strong> — Africa skips old infrastructure stages. Mobile money before credit cards. Solar before the grid. 4G before landlines in many communities.</li>
<li><strong>Informal economy</strong> — 80%+ of economic activity in many countries is informal. Serving market traders, artisans, and small business owners is a massive and underserved market.</li>
<li><strong>Agent networks</strong> — In markets with low formal infrastructure, human agents (shopkeepers, kiosks) become your distribution channel. M-PESA, OPay, and Moniepoint mastered this.</li>
<li><strong>Community trust</strong> — Business runs on personal relationships and community reputation. Building trust through community involvement is not optional — it is competitive strategy.</li>
</ul>
<h3>The African Startup Ecosystem</h3>
<p>Lagos, Nairobi, Cairo, and Johannesburg are the four main hubs. Combined African startup funding exceeded $5 billion in 2022. Flutterwave reached unicorn status. Andela, Twiga Foods, Chipper Cash, Wave, and many others are transforming their sectors. The ecosystem is young but compounding rapidly.</p>
<h3>AfCFTA — The Continental Opportunity</h3>
<p>The African Continental Free Trade Area creates the world's largest free trade zone across 54 countries and 1.4 billion people. For founders, products built in Nigeria can serve customers in Kenya without heavy tariffs — the entire continent becomes your market.</p>
<div class="africa-box"><span class="africa-title">&#127757; Key Numbers</span>
Nigeria: 37M+ SMEs, 48% of GDP. Kenya: M-PESA serves 40M+ users. Egypt: $600M+ startup funding in 2022. Ghana: Fastest growing fintech market per capita in West Africa. The continent needs 100M+ new jobs by 2030 — entrepreneurs will create them.
</div>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Leapfrogging</strong> — Skipping older tech stages to adopt the latest solutions directly<br>
<strong>Informal economy</strong> — Legitimate activity outside formal taxation and regulation<br>
<strong>Agent banking</strong> — Using local human agents as banking and service access points<br>
<strong>AfCFTA</strong> — African Continental Free Trade Area
