  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-25" data-lesson="25"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(25)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-25">25</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Ethics, Social Impact, and Sustainable Business</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">Triple bottom line, CSR, B Corp, greenwashing, data ethics, impact</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-25"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-25">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-25"><h3>Ethics is Strategy</h3>
<p>Ethical companies attract better talent, build stronger customer loyalty, access impact capital, and avoid regulatory crises that destroy unethical businesses. In Africa, where trust is scarce, ethical business practices are a genuine competitive advantage.</p>
<h3>The Triple Bottom Line</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Profit</strong> — Financial sustainability. You must make money to pursue your mission.</li>
<li><strong>People</strong> — Impact on employees, communities, and society.</li>
<li><strong>Planet</strong> — Environmental impact and responsibility.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Building an Ethical Business</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Transparency</strong> — Honest about what you can and cannot do. Underpromise, overdeliver.</li>
<li><strong>Fair pricing</strong> — Do not exploit customers, especially vulnerable populations.</li>
<li><strong>Data ethics</strong> — Collect only what you need. Protect it rigorously. Never sell user data without explicit consent.</li>
<li><strong>Supply chain ethics</strong> — Know where your materials come from. No child labour. Fair wages at every level.</li>
<li><strong>Inclusive design</strong> — Build products that work for people with different abilities, languages, and connectivity levels.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Social Enterprise Models</h3>
<p>Social enterprises use commercial mechanisms to achieve social goals: M-PESA — financial inclusion. Andela — tech talent creation. Twiga Foods — reducing food waste and improving farmer income. They prove that doing good and doing well are not opposites.</p>
<h3>Greenwashing Warning</h3>
<p>Greenwashing is making misleading claims about environmental responsibility. As sustainability becomes mainstream, the temptation to claim green credentials without substance is high. Customers and investors increasingly see through it — and the reputational damage is severe.</p>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>Triple Bottom Line</strong> — People, Planet, and Profit as three success dimensions<br>
<strong>B Corporation</strong> — Certified company meeting high social and environmental standards<br>
<strong>Greenwashing</strong> — Misleading claims about environmental responsibility<br>
<strong>Impact investing</strong> — Investment seeking social outcomes alongside financial returns
