  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-27" data-lesson="27"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(27)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-27">27</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Negotiation for Entrepreneurs</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">BATNA, ZOPA, anchoring, win-win, investor terms, supplier deals</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-27"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-27">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-27"><h3>Why Negotiation is a Core Founder Skill</h3>
<p>Founders negotiate constantly: investor term sheets, co-founder agreements, customer contracts, supplier terms, office leases, employee salaries, and partnership deals. Every negotiation shapes your business's future. Poor negotiators leave enormous value on the table.</p>
<h3>Key Negotiation Concepts</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>BATNA (Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement)</strong> — Your backup if talks fail. The stronger your BATNA, the more power you hold. Never negotiate without knowing yours.</li>
<li><strong>ZOPA (Zone of Possible Agreement)</strong> — The range where both parties would accept a deal. No overlap = no deal possible.</li>
<li><strong>Interests vs Positions</strong> — A position is what someone says they want. An interest is why. Negotiating on interests opens creative solutions both prefer.</li>
<li><strong>Anchoring</strong> — The first number stated becomes the psychological reference point. Set it strategically.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Practical Tactics</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Silence</strong> — After making an offer, stop talking. Silence creates pressure to respond and often improves terms.</li>
<li><strong>Flinch</strong> — Visibly react to an offer to signal it is unacceptable — often triggers an immediate improvement.</li>
<li><strong>Bundle issues</strong> — Negotiate price, payment terms, and service level together to create room for trade-offs.</li>
<li><strong>Walk-away</strong> — Being genuinely willing to walk away is your strongest negotiating position.</li>
</ul>
