ctOption(this,27,5,1,1)">Creates pressure on the other party to respond and often leads to better terms</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,5,2,1)">It ends the negotiation</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,5,3,1)">Signals agreement</div></div><div class="q-feedback" id="qf-27-5"></div></div><div class="quiz-q" id="q-27-6"><div class="q-text"><span class="q-num">Q7</span>Win-win negotiation means?</div><div class="q-options"><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,6,0,1)">Both parties get exactly what they asked for</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,6,1,1)">Both parties achieve their most important underlying interests</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,6,2,1)">A compromise where both sides lose something major</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,6,3,1)">Only one party wins but they are happy about it</div></div><div class="q-feedback" id="qf-27-6"></div></div><div class="quiz-q" id="q-27-7"><div class="q-text"><span class="q-num">Q8</span>Why is being willing to walk away powerful?</div><div class="q-options"><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,7,0,1)">It is rude and damages relationships</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,7,1,1)">It removes desperation and gives you full negotiating leverage — you genuinely do not need this specific deal</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,7,2,1)">It always leads to better terms guaranteed</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,7,3,1)">It should only be used as a bluff</div></div><div class="q-feedback" id="qf-27-7"></div></div><div class="quiz-q" id="q-27-8"><div class="q-text"><span class="q-num">Q9</span>When should you anchor high in a negotiation?</div><div class="q-options"><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,8,0,1)">Never anchor — let them go first</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,8,1,1)">When you are selling — set a high reference point that makes your actual price seem reasonable</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,8,2,1)">Only in salary negotiations</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,8,3,1)">When you are in a weak position</div></div><div class="q-feedback" id="qf-27-8"></div></div><div class="quiz-q" id="q-27-9"><div class="q-text"><span class="q-num">Q10</span>What is the most critical preparation before any negotiation?</div><div class="q-options"><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,9,0,1)">Memorising aggressive tactics</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,9,1,1)">Researching both your position and the other party's interests, constraints, and alternatives</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,9,2,1)">Deciding never to compromise</div><div class="q-option" onclick="selectOption(this,27,9,3,1)">Bringing a lawyer to every meeting</div></div><div class="q-feedback" id="qf-27-9"></div></div></div><div class="quiz-actions"><span class="quiz-answered-count" id="qcount-27"><span>0</span>/10 answered</span><button class="quiz-submit-btn" id="qsub-27" onclick="submitQuiz(27)" disabled>Submit Test &#8594;</button></div><div class="quiz-result" id="qres-27" style="display:none"></div></div></div></div>

  <div class="lesson-card locked" id="lcard-28" data-lesson="28"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson(28)"><div class="lesson-num" id="lnum-28">28</div><div class="lesson-info"><div class="lesson-title">Technology for Non-Technical Founders</div><div class="lesson-subtitle">APIs, SaaS, no-code, cloud, AI tools, cybersecurity, building tech products</div></div><div class="lesson-status" id="lstatus-28"><span class="lock-icon">&#128274;</span></div><div class="lesson-toggle" id="ltoggle-28">&#8964;</div></div><div class="lesson-body" id="lbody-28"><h3>You Do Not Need to Code to Build a Tech Company</h3>
<p>Many of the most successful tech company founders are non-technical. What you need is: enough understanding to communicate clearly with developers, evaluate solutions critically, and avoid being misled about timelines, complexity, or cost.</p>
<h3>Essential Concepts</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Frontend vs Backend</strong> — Frontend is what users see and interact with. Backend is the server, database, and logic running behind the scenes.</li>
<li><strong>API (Application Programming Interface)</strong> — How software systems communicate. Flutterwave's API lets you add payments to any app without building payment infrastructure yourself.</li>
<li><strong>Cloud computing</strong> — Rent computing power from AWS, Google Cloud, or Azure instead of buying servers. Start small, scale instantly, pay as you grow.</li>
<li><strong>SaaS (Software as a Service)</strong> — Software accessed via the internet on subscription. Use SaaS tools to operate before building custom software.</li>
<li><strong>Database</strong> — Where your data lives. SQL (structured: orders, users) and NoSQL (flexible: real-time data) are the two main types.</li>
</ul>
<h3>No-Code Tools for Founders</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Webflow</strong> — Build professional websites without code</li>
<li><strong>Bubble</strong> — Build fully functional web apps without code</li>
<li><strong>Glide</strong> — Turn spreadsheets into mobile apps</li>
<li><strong>Zapier / Make</strong> — Automate workflows between apps</li>
<li><strong>Airtable</strong> — Powerful database-spreadsheet hybrid</li>
</ul>
<h3>Essential Startup Software Stack</h3>
<ul>
<li>CRM: HubSpot (free tier) — manage customer relationships</li>
<li>Payments: Flutterwave or Paystack — accept payments instantly</li>
<li>Communication: Slack (team) + WhatsApp (customers)</li>
<li>Analytics: Google Analytics (web) + Mixpanel (product)</li>
<li>Productivity: Notion — docs, databases, project management</li>
</ul>
<div class="glossary-box"><span class="gls-title">// Glossary</span>
<strong>API</strong> — Application Programming Interface: how systems communicate<br>
<strong>SaaS</strong> — Software as a Service: cloud software on subscription<br>
<strong>No-code</strong> — Building products without writing traditional code<br>
<strong>Technical debt</strong> — Code shortcuts that create significant rework cost later
